To start a new process in C++ with one file descriptor connected to its input and output, you can use the `fork()` and `dup2()` functions. Here's a basic example:

```cpp
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main() {
    int fd[2];
    pipe(fd);  // Create a pipe

    pid_t pid = fork();  // Fork a new process

    if (pid == -1) {
        perror("fork");
        return 1;
    } else if (pid == 0) {  // Child process
        close(fd[1]);  // Close the write end in the child
        dup2(fd[0], 0);  // Duplicate the read end to stdin
        dup2(fd[0], 1);  // Duplicate the read end to stdout
        close(fd[0]);  // Close the read end
        execlp("command", "command", (char*)0);  // Run a command
        perror("execlp");
        return 1;
    } else {  // Parent process
        close(fd[0]);  // Close the read end in the parent
        // Do something with the write end if needed
        wait(NULL);  // Wait for the child to finish
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, replace `"command"` with the command you want to run. This code sets up a pipe, forges a new process, and connects the pipe to the child's standard input and output. The parent process then waits for the child to finish.
